_children.explanation:
Be – 1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>2</sup>; 
<br><br>B – 1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>2</sup>2p<sup>1</sup>; 
<br><br>C – 1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>2</sup>2p<sup>2</sup>; 
<br><br>N – 1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>2</sup>2p<sup>3</sup>; 
<br><br>O – 1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>2</sup>2p<sup>4</sup>. 
<br><br>IP increases along the period. But IP of Be &gt; B. Further IP of O &lt; N because atoms with fully  or partly filled orbitals are most stable and hence have high ionisation energy. 
<br><br>As in case of boron, 2p<sup>1</sup> electron have to be removed to get B<sup>+</sup>(1s<sup>2</sup> 2s<sup>2</sup>) 
 from B(1s<sup>2</sup> 2s<sup>2</sup> 2p<sup>1</sup>), while in case of Be (1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>2</sup>) electron have to be removed to get Be<sup>+</sup> (1s<sup>2</sup>2s<sup>1</sup>). p electron can be removed more easily than s electron so the energy required to remove electron will be less in case of boron.
